 say=\r\n Gayatri mantra out loud.&lt;br&gt;\n&lt;br&gt;When he transmits the mantra, he should e=\r\nnsure that only the young man hears it and nobody else does (i.e. no diluti=\r\non in the transmitted energy). The custom is to say it in the ear while a c=\r\nloth covers both, but that only *symbolizes* secretiveness and may not real=\r\nly *ensure* secretiveness. If everybody (especially the priest) is sitting =\r\nclose to them, they may also hear it in spite of a the cloth covering them.=\r\n&lt;br&gt;\n&lt;br&gt;When I did upanayanam to my son, we did the rituals in open air in=\r\n our back yard. At the time of brahmopadesa muhurta, I took my son inside t=\r\nhe pooja room where I did my sadhana. I did not allow anybody, including th=\r\ne priests, to come there. I taught the mantra to my son in an low, but audi=\r\nble, voice. I repeated a few times, made him repeat it a few times, ensured=\r\n his pronunciation was correct, and then both of us did a maalaa (108 times=\r\n meditation) with it silently. We then came back to the backyard and the ri=\r\ntuals continued.&lt;br&gt;\n&lt;br&gt;One more thing on muhurta: If you got a muhurta fr=\r\nom an astrologer you trust and want to follow it, please ensure that Gayatr=\r\ni mantra is taught at that muhurta. THAT is the main event. Some priests pu=\r\nt a paste made of cumin seeds and jaggery on the young man&#39;s head at th=\r\ne muhurta time. That is irrelevant and brahmopadesa is the main thing.&lt;br&gt;\n=\r\n&lt;br&gt;* * *&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Though we did a detailed ritual for my son&#39;s upanayana=\r\nm, my own upanayanam was a very simple affair. Though my father is an ortho=\r\ndox braahmana following a very simple and austere lifestyle, he is unorthod=\r\nox in the matter of rituals. Above all, he fearlessly follows his convictio=\r\nns and does not engage in rituals that he does not consider meaningful. He =\r\nis also against following the letter of the rules and breaking the spirit. =\r\nFor exa